:"Devereux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, Sean.","English and Irish: of Norman origin, a habitational name for someone from Évreux in Eure, France, with the preposition <i>d(e)</i>. See also   Everest   for the name without the preposition.","History: This was the surname of the Earls of Essex from 1572 to 1641. Walter <i>Devereux</i>, 1st Earl of Essex, led an attempted colonization of Ulster, and his son, Robert, 2nd Earl of Essex, briefly held the position of lord lieutenant of Ireland in 1599."],"variants":[{"name":"Devereaux","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Devereux  ."]},{"name":"Everest","meanings":["English (southeastern): of Norman origin, a variant of   Devereux   without the fused preposition (Old French <i>de</i>). Compare   Evers  ."]},{"name":"Evers","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Devereux   without the fused preposition (Old French <i>de</i>).","English: de-aspirated variant of <b>Heaver</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a habitational name from Hever (Kent), named from Old English <i>hēah</i> ‘high’ + (Kentish) Old English <i>ēfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill’. Alternatively, the name may derive from some minor place in southeastern England named with Old English <i>ȳfre</i>, (Kentish) Old English <i>ēfre</i>, Middle English <i>evere</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, with the addition of a prosthetic <i>H-</i>.","North German and Dutch: genitivized patronymic from the personal name   Evert  , which lost its <i>t</i> in pronunciation and spelling subsequently; compare   Everts  . Compare also   Avers  ."]},{"name":"Deveraux","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Devereux  ."]},{"name":"Devery","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Kieran, Brendan, Clancy.","Irish (Offaly): of Norman origin, a variant of   Devereux  ."]},{"name":"Devary","meanings":["Probably Irish: variant of <b>Devery</b>, a variant of   Devereux   in counties Leix and Offaly."]},{"name":"Debrow","meanings":["Altered form of English or Irish   Devereux  ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":2,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":33,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda Devereux was born about 1257, in Herefordshire, England. She married Walter de la Barre about 1278, in Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died after 1299."},"et":{"about 1257–after 1299":"